Food Due to European Inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, the cost was higher than expected in November – after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are assuming only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered Leitzsins, which it believes will lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the midst of a crisis: Inflation needs to be “decided” in order to exclude the need for action at a later date.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in November in Germany reached a twelve-year record high; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is caused by the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat listings rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts assume a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
