Many places are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overloading of staff - all factors that are not directly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
Many places are also saved with disinfectants.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection here.
The injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with a MRSA infection. An important operation has since not been performed due to the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By December 10 of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, but the dark digits are likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, almond inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or applied inappropriately, the well-responsive bacteria form antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with a weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in the elderly, or in patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the daily routine of the hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA just does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are being isolated, the nursing staff are wearing rubber gloves and masks in care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are tested for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples taken too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection mainly occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the delivered patients and isolate MRSA-infected immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Last but not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Therefore, most cases would only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among outpatients or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most often transmitted by caregivers from one patient to another.
This is why handwashing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by drip cell infection or contact, but there is not always a possibility to isolate the infected patient in local hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that even favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government Program Against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurance huge costs, so they are being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was retained in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections is declining in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
