Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the measures to reduce emissions for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiration of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between industrialized and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be ready to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support the developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on support to developing countries.
The adjustment fund subject to the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, expected to be in the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s commitment to maintaining its leading role in global climate action and to reaching a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured in 1990 values), regardless of whether or not the "Agreement after 2012" will be successfully achieved. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction if other large industrial countries in the world are committed to complying with their obligations.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the states that had acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, while the EU with its then 15 member states had already committed to a minus of 8 per cent.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will fully meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly enter into force only after 2012. In this case, the report would not follow the new, international climate reduction system set out in the Kyoto Protocol.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and an increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, is checked at the Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where it is put on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defence headquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Department of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign deployments.
Propaganda of this kind is almost free compared to conventional television commercials, defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise With Game
But the army must also fight against amateur footage, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage, also creates it on the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not told.
By the way, numerous videos shot on the platform have already been uploaded from the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, but this "genre" has only recently been discovered by the British.
Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooter "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
