Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to a short-term ethnic conflict".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "Persons of public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is assumed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, "have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been constantly on the rise, so that since summer 2007, several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been established.
"It is common for these groups to define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly boasting that they are preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (disaster protection, national defense, law enforcement), invoking the inadequacy of the state police, the armed forces themselves," he said.
And further: all this is done according to that method, which tries to disguise as a bourgeois initiative various political aspirations based on the political and party aspirations of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association is therefore not merely to circumvent legal obstacles that may arise during the registration process - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, as some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as the confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background of the creation of the Bulgarian Guard was the mass outbreaks of Roma, which took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organization was "national protection".
