Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of re-disposing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but next year will provide us with fewer such days.
In the EU and in America, something else is understood as "Holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are working days - the latter alone so that the New Year celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year, we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The national holidays are March 15, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the foundation of the state, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays to Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working days shifting" has proven to be proven in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holidays, is finally to be worked out, for many years the Minister of Labour has set in its own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public servants and civil servants alike.
Excepted are only companies and facilities where the operation is continued without interruption, including on public holidays.
This year, the rules of work are only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in this country remains formal, as most take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holidays specifically cancelled for it.
Next year there will be more holidays in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-arrangements on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "put on the head" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second re-arrangement is related to the holiday on October 23: On Saturday, October 18, you will have to work on Friday, October 24 in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be marked by the holidays, after December 24, everything will lie and stand still, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six deterrent little things to annoy co-workers
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never get - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring "color" into everyday life at work.
