Banks want to deal with the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the crisis in the financial markets together.
This means that more than $100 billion will reach the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, the banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the US Fed sends $40 billion to auction, another 24 makes it loose for the European and Swiss central bank.
It is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to deter or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties in the economy, i.e. the growing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," said Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in a report for its clients.
“The coordinated action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to non-performing loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are expecting billions more.
"The central banks must have really been afraid of what else could happen when they decided to do this," said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into recession, possibly with an impact on economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London Interbank Rate, which is used for lending money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid of lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as further interest rate cuts," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this move by the central banks is contributing to the warming of the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the real estate market in the United States.
