Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you only choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and enchanting cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the prohibition) was liked to be seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, over the wide boulevards cars drove, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
What about today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
At the bar at Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails to your liking.
And the cult cars of the fifties drive around in Havana to this day, because the once imported schigulis and fiats have long since collapsed in the salty and damp air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have fallen sharply, nowhere in the vicinity can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are just being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a Marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauges to the sugar factories.
Its fleet has not been renewed for decades, so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have been in the museum for a long time.
Excursion Destinations
The most important places do not leave out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
You don’t have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
Just to mention that in the already mentioned estate of Hemingway there is a museum, the visit of which should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which even weathered rock areas are covered by dense growth.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also be interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the TV series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad and Tobago
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
The slave trade and the sugar trade brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth embodied in the beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has barely changed in four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is a place so remote that there was no road connecting the area to the rest of the country until the 1950s.
This isolation contributed to it being disregarded.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the "valley of sugar factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which comes to life after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is described by some as the most beautiful of the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads that lead there from Guantánamo have to overcome high and steep mountains and pass through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage List thanks to its pristine nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in fact it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the present Hotel El Castillo, you can see several table-mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the Island of Pinos, the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess themselves, you could yell many pages about all this.
But, as they say, look better with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
Too few soldiers and the lack of the necessary equipment affects the course of the mission in Afghanistan, according to the United States.
NATO should, in the words of Defense Secretary Robert Gates, draw up a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan did not go according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries that stationed units in the south of the country in Edinburgh, Scotland, agreed on this.
In addition to the growing resistance on the part of the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called for more activity by NATO units, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and in intensifying development aid.
“In Afghanistan, a forward development is noticeable, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to enable residents to start developing the economy and security themselves,” British Defense Secretary Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the U.S. Army.
The number of violent actions has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
The NATO countries have deployed about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the Allies have come to an absolute limit in terms of the organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they call for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan units.
"We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next time and about the way we can achieve them," Gates said.
The Secretary-General of NATO, Jaap de Hoop, said the same thing today.
“I am not pleased with what we have available in Afghanistan on land and in the air.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we need, and that’s too little,” De Hoop told Reuters at the conclusion of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is Passive
Among the countries involved, there has also been a dispute over whether all allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
Germany, for example, has been criticized for its passivity.
“The Germans are relatively numerous in Afghanistan.
But they are stationed in areas where there is only a minimum of violence and the fighting requirements for them are not as high as for us in the southern and eastern parts of the country," Gates said.
The British Boulevard newspaper "Sun" this week described the German soldiers as lazy.
"Afghan non-storm disguises: The Germans are playing games while our boys are fighting," the "Sun" wrote in a post, which was supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
