Government debt will accelerate to one trillion in 2009
The Czech Republic owes a total of 84,000 crowns to the government.
Total debt rose to CZK 842.7 billion by the end of September.
The government had planned to owe 159.2 billion cones this year.
However, at the beginning of December, the Ministry reduced the plan to $152.8 billion thanks to better development of state budget policy.
The government debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion kroner by the end of September.
In the first nine months of this year, they increased by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Treasury Department confirmed its data on government debt in early October.
A debt of SEK 84000 is owed to each Czech.
Over the entire past year, the state owed more than 111 billion crowns.
"Until now, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for the coming year, we may not cross the one trillion kroner limit until 2009.
Next year the debt should move between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, told iHNed.cz.
Similarly, Vladimír Pikora, analyst at Next Finance: "We could exceed one trillion in 2009.
When exactly depends on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it turns out that the situation on the political stage is changing, and politicians should be willing to save more, that could take until 2010.
But I am not assuming such a change," he noted.
Debt grows
State debt comes from the debts of the state government and mainly comes from the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The government debt is financed by treasury notes, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, by bonds from the European Investment Bank.
Domestic government debt has risen to SEK 719.4 billion this year.
The government’s foreign debt has risen by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable sovereign debt reached CZK 803.3 billion at the end of September and has fallen by CZK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of government debt increased to 6.5 years.
“Total debt rose by 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting that the growth is mainly recorded in the bonds, where the growth is 20 percent.
It’s bad that debts are rising, but on the other hand, this shows that something can be done before the pension reform comes,” Pikora commented on the data.
Better Than Expected
The financing strategy and government debt management for 2007 show that the government had planned to raise 159.2 billion kronor for this year.
However, at the beginning of December, the Ministry reduced the plan to CZK 152.8 billion, thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
This is mainly due to the government budget deficit, which this year will obviously reach SEK 76 billion instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
This includes a maximum amount of 13.3 billion kroner for the Consolidation Agency, a ten billion reserve to pay pensions, 43 billion for sovereign debt and 1.8 billion for bonds with the European Investment Bank.
For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher accused of insulting Islam in Sudan was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Muhammad, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be beaten.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum was picked up at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this issue begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, school principal Robert Boules reports.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Surely, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Subsequently, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the image caption My name is Mohammed .
The bear itself did not bear a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, stated that he knows her well and she would never have done anything that could have brought her too close to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion it is only a mistake and a matter of guilt.
An opinion shared by numerous students of the teacher who describe her as being very attentive to her students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common second name in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This surname, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of homage to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
At the last negotiating meeting in Vienna on Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the End of Failure
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians ended a sixth and final discussion session in Baden, Austria, Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversy over the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties were unable to reach an agreement on the status, European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their commitments to maintain peace, and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, indicating that there are quite clear tensions.
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the United States and Russia, will meet for the last time on Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, formed the sixth and final negotiating session since the troika had been ordered by the UN last August to conduct a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo's independence to the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
Russia has been and remains an advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years under UN administration, the Western countries consider EU-supervised independence to be the only solution for the future.
Pristina is willing to declare them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where since Monday these negotiations were the last chance.
Hashim Thaci, a former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
However, he added that the plan proposed by Belgrade for autonomy belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino Effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, believed that a compromise should always be sought, and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that it is particularly provoking a “domino effect” in a region that is still so much weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision would be taken solely and exclusively in the Security Council, where their Russian ally holds a veto.
Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word
Only a decision from the ranks of the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations lasted two years.
They have to end the way they started: in the Security Council.
To the journalists, Fatmir Sejdiu replied that the Kosovo Parliament will have the last word on the status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population will be conducted in coordination with the Western countries.
Bush Reveals Israeli-Palestinian Deal
At the opening of the international peace conference, which he chaired in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He further stated that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do anything to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy the terrorist infrastructure and Israel must stop its colonization work, Bush said, reminding the two parties of their commitments to the peace roadmap they agreed to in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that will clarify all open issues without exception, including the central issues.
This designation encompasses the three serious problems that the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve around: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of Arab refugees displaced from their homeland in the course of the 1948 conflict, which became the present-day state of Israel.
After the American President, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement on all points, including listing Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert, in turn, took the floor, he pledged that the upcoming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption, and that he would endeavour to end them before the end of 2008.
Bush has set a deadline for the implementation of his vision of two states, a Palestinian and an Israeli, which exist side by side, by the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has revealed that it has received assurances from Bush in this sense before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has embarked on a plan adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace, in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis represents a turning point in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central points of view, the Saudi prince said in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily newspaper.
