Spectacular repairs at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a faulty solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A bold exit that, due to its duration, the distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools built by the astronauts to carry out the repair, has achieved several records.
The problem occurred on Wednesday when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that will soon accommodate the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module labs.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5-tonne module for power generation via solar panels, which was already on the ISS, in order to bring it to its final position.
After displacing it, the crew proceeded to restructure the module’s solar panels with a span of 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be folded up like accordions, was damaged by a clamped cable over a length of about one meter.
Restructuring was stopped to avoid further damage to the collector.
Astronauts who originally left the Discovery space shuttle for a check-in and then had to repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the 30-metre-long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skilled, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
So the 46-year-old trained doctor was selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully assessing the damage, he cut through the faulty cable and fastened some sort of rail on the damaged site.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained close to the lock, and, from the inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick, wrapped with an insulator to prevent electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, had been conceived and crafted by the astronauts aboard the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully unfolded before counting down his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation before today seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery, expected to embark on the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
