A heavy reminder
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven government-appointed states – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for investigations, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the state of health of forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental impairment of some deportation victims.
The prisoner lists of the concentration camps or the detention orders issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new is to be expected in these documents, Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
