Following numerous rumors about the creation of a new music festival in Philadelphia by C3 Presents, the promoter/producer announces the Vineland Music Festival in New Jersey, in collaboration with Festival Republic of British producer Melvin Benn.
It is an honor for our company to work with a person who has served, no more and no less, as a role model for the current festival movement in America, Charlie Jones of C3 told Bilboard.com.
C3 hosts the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
Vineland, New Jersey, is a summer destination for camping holidays.
The festival will take place from August 8-10 on a 500-acre private farm about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
The director of Festival Republic Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the producers of the most prestigious festivals in the world.
In 1989, he took over the leadership of the Reading Festival in the United Kingdom, which attracts around 80,000 people annually.
In 1999, Melvin Benn added the Leeds Festival to his portfolio, and then, in 2006, Festival Republic created the Latitude Festival at Henham Park in Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn, as co-owner, has also taken care of production, licensing concessions and organizational tasks for the Glastonbury Festival, which can now accommodate up to 177,500 people.
Charlie Jones of C3, who describes Glastonbury as the most inspiring event he has ever attended, says his company and that of Melvin Benn are working side by side to offer the area a European-style festival event.
“We have chosen Philadelphia as a market and are eagerly working with the Fairmount Park Commission to create a festival in downtown Philadelphia,” says Charlie Jones.
We were negotiating with the city and the Commission was motivated and enthusiastic about this project.
Unfortunately, we have been stuck in political debates regarding the current administration, Charlie Jones continues.
“Fortunately, we were able to discuss with Melvin Benn and we are meeting preparations to create a great festival in an extraordinary place that will ultimately benefit the population.”
C3 Presents has brought the Lollapalooza Festival back to life in 2005 at Grand Park Chicago after it, together with the Austin City Limits Music Festival, became a part of the festival world in 2002.
The two events were able to generate $9.8 million and $11.8 million respectively in gross tax days in 2007.
These two festivals take place in an urban setting.
“Melvin Benn’s European model is a rural festival, whereas ours is more on urban green spaces,” says Charlie Jones.
"The goal is to merge these two concepts in one way or another, to simultaneously convey the impression of a rural festival on the European and an urban one on the American way."
Vineland is about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“The Vineland community, including the mayor, is happy to take on the burden of this event,” says Charlie Jones.
The latter refuses to disclose the terms of the agreement, but he confirms that "they are interesting enough to invest in such an event and host a festival that will hopefully have a long life."
Charlie Jones says the festival's reception capacity is "very large", corresponding to the approximately 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
He says that the invitations have been sent to the groups, but that nothing could be confirmed when they were printed.
“Vineland will offer tasteful rock, but the music will be very diverse in the hope of attracting all kinds of spectators,” says Charlie Jones.
His partners from C3, who won the Top Independent Promoter Award of the last Bollboard Touring Awards, are Charlie Walker and Charles Attal.
