New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is swelling between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are conducted by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for imports from Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drastically pushed prices up.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of pre-trial detention records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the supervisory body.
The recommendation of Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish state health service does not have a precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a SUV drove through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to conduct checks prior to hiring foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review pre-trial records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the chief auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the board should adopt guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out," the report said.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines before hiring, but added: “Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health workers is available.”
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to hiring potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
“The report says NHS Scotland’s current pre-employment tests are working well and it’s not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver,” he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards had problems identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation further found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been predominantly complied with.
This includes passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Secretary of Health Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern for me to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices in updated guidelines regarding check-ups before hiring all staff - including those from abroad next month - would be reflected in their publication.
