The climate on Venus could show a glimpse into the future of the Earth
Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit show that the planet resembles an Earth-turned-away twin even more than previously known.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But due to the unrestrained carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by sunlight and a slower rotational rate, Venus took a completely different course of evolution.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express space probe, which examined the plant for a year, provide a sobering insight into how the Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
“Our new data allow us to construct a scenario in which Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment.”
