Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No nobles seem to have been sold, no politicians in Paris paid hotel bills, no extramarital toes stolen.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has veiled donations to the British ruling Labour Party over more than <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which competing Gordon Brown would have done well.
When the Prime Minister withdrew from the demand for an election two months ago, foolishly insulting the British intelligence by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced that decision, there was hope that it would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly keen Liberal Democrat representative, put it, the once-feared Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The unskilled rescue of Northern Rock, a beleaguered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend the tax laws have provoked corporate associations against the government.
The tax authorities’ loss of 25 million people’s personal data showed unimaginable administrative fraud.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest of cuts in military spending: being a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the diverse donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s Secretary General (and her former Chief Executive) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown irrevocably sets off in the direction of resignation.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point where they feel it is impossible to govern.
Neither do people like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new troop takes office.
Once it is clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn’t even need to be there for long, this postponement is over: public service is starting to leak; cabinet ministers are starting to chatter; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he can’t claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wanted to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-general.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction records, for example, are related to decisions that Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s misfortune – as in the long “money for nobility” investigation of political party funding – voters may assume that he was.
However, Brown’s situation is not as bad as it looks.
The faults are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely cheated.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what of course Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new witness for political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be the case, but he was not allowed to make the decision.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and they exist for one clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham’s deal but didn’t say it was illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s chief financial officer, who was told about the odd donations in October.
But so far, Brown has not been involved: there is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted that determination by grasping for a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject—to fill the measure—by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a comprehensive reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of the Labour Party to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to give up the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve a victory is through indisputable integrity and solid competence.
