Is the credit crisis affecting America’s credit card market?
When blood is in the water, it’s only natural that spinal fleas swirl excitedly around.
Now that America’s real estate market is crippled, predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both the payouts and the salary rates, which measure the share of loans that are non-recognizable or more than 30 days late in each case.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its U.S. consumer financing, partly due to the weakness of credit card borrowers.
It is still too early to panic.
Losses and losses are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody’s, the third-quarter growth rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency law in 2005 resulted in an abrupt case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large part of the tedious card losses; the number of filings (and hence tuition fees) would rise again whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorated.
The industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of its debt consumers pay off each month
and the confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research firm, expects that spending for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infectious channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt now that home loans are dried up.
However, card issuers look at the cash flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the creditworthiness of the borrower.
They can even be advantageous for card issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates will decrease if the properties are less valuable than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to stormier conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and completely reassess the loans,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden cover-up crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustainable downturn are considerably more real.
If lower house prices and a credit cut push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
