Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its life-threatening atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has detected flashes in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe “Venus Express” has provided the evidence – it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus shoots at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine “Nature”.
According to the famous "Ursuppen theory", lightning bolts created life on Earth: storms in the ocean are said to have triggered reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
“If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” said Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes with temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the Earth's devil twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has evolved so completely differently is the basic question of the ESA mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus exploration, as no probe has been on its way to explore this planet since the early 1990s.
The latest research findings, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially assumed," the ESA said in a statement.
In addition to the already well-known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air flows in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second thinnest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large as the Earth with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in nearly 225 days.
It revolves much slower around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in the oceans, but on which Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
