These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and Wooden Box thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
Most of the ninety-four "Type Stockholm" brillo boxes listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago, Kunstox International has raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of the year 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: the six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has also published in 1995.
Prehistory is intertwined, a confusing link between artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the soap powder cartons "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, exhibited hundreds of brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but models of them, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses are now talking about about fifteen boxes, which at the time entered art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 on auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, three of which were privately owned in Sweden, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first ground and glazed off, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press plate with a paint roller without a primer - moreover, it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says Moderna Museum Director Lars Nittve, "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the copy of the Moderna Museum's material will be removed."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the “heavy accusations” raised in the case of the soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have remained inexorably silent.
